26
00:01:55,960 --> 00:01:59,480
But, our story begins in
19th-century Germany and Austria

27
00:01:59,480 --> 00:02:01,880
with the music of Brahms and
Bruckner,

28
00:02:01,880 --> 00:02:08,160
two giant pillars
of the great Germanic tradition
and musical descendants of JS Bach.

29
00:02:08,160 --> 00:02:13,560
They were composers of great
conviction, makers of music
both sacred and secular.

30
00:02:13,560 --> 00:02:17,080
But two men who could not have
been more different.

31
00:02:17,080 --> 00:02:22,720
# Ecce sacerdos, magnus... #

32
00:02:22,720 --> 00:02:27,640
Anton Bruckner, born in the secure
heartland of a declining
Austrian Empire,

33
00:02:27,640 --> 00:02:32,840
was a devout Catholic
all his life and his music is a
confident affirmation of his faith.

34
00:02:38,640 --> 00:02:41,880
And, Johannes Brahms,
a north German Protestant.

35
00:02:41,880 --> 00:02:46,480
He confidently addressed
questions of faith, death,
and human existence.

36
00:02:46,480 --> 00:02:51,520
But, ultimately, found himself
unable to believe in anything
but his music.

37
00:02:51,520 --> 00:03:00,680
# Mit Fried und Freud
ich fahr dahin

38
00:03:00,680 --> 00:03:09,960
# In Gottes Willen... #

39
00:03:12,880 --> 00:03:16,440
By the end of his life, Johannes
Brahms had secured his reputation

40
00:03:16,440 --> 00:03:20,040
as a great composer
and a master of the symphony.

41
00:03:20,040 --> 00:03:25,640
But his early career
was launched by his less well known
sacred choral music.

42
00:03:25,640 --> 00:03:31,040
Work that is deeply personal,
profoundly human,
and distinctly German.

43
00:03:36,240 --> 00:03:39,720
So, I've travelled to his hometown
of Hamburg,

44
00:03:39,720 --> 00:03:41,520
the second largest city in Germany.

45
00:03:44,400 --> 00:03:48,480
In 1833, somewhere around here
in Speckstrasse,

46
00:03:48,480 --> 00:03:53,760
then known as Specksgang, or
Bacon Alley, Johannes was born.

47
00:03:55,040 --> 00:04:00,400
MUSIC: Piano Concerto No. 1 in
D Minor, Op 15, by Johannes Brahms

48
00:04:03,560 --> 00:04:08,000
Johannes' parents were
essentially a respectable
working class couple.

49
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:11,360
But the area they lived in
was desperately impoverished.

50
00:04:11,360 --> 00:04:14,160
Frankly, a slum.

51
00:04:15,600 --> 00:04:18,600
His father was charming
and good-looking.

52
00:04:18,600 --> 00:04:22,160
He worked as a bugler for the town
militia and as a "bier fiddler" -

53
00:04:22,160 --> 00:04:27,480
a mildly contemptuous term
for someone who plays music in the
streets, and in bars and cafes.

54
00:04:33,560 --> 00:04:37,120
Christiane, his mother, was
17 years older than her husband

55
00:04:37,120 --> 00:04:40,000
and had probably given
up any hope of marriage.

56
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:43,920
She was, however, a good
cook and housekeeper,
and an excellent seamstress.

57
00:04:43,920 --> 00:04:48,800
Not particularly prepossessing
to look at, she did have
clear, sparkling, blue eyes.

58
00:04:48,800 --> 00:04:51,520
A characteristic
inherited by her son.

59
00:04:58,800 --> 00:05:04,000
By the time he was 13 years old,
Johannes was already
a pretty accomplished pianist.

60
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:06,960
It seems he was sent
off to play in the Lokale,

61
00:05:06,960 --> 00:05:14,320
bars in the St Pauli district
around here that also served as
cafes, coffee houses, dance halls

62
00:05:14,320 --> 00:05:16,200
and brothels.

63
00:05:19,120 --> 00:05:23,160
Later in life, he would describe
his childhood as a curse.

64
00:05:23,160 --> 00:05:26,760
But he also said
that he didn't regret it.

65
00:05:26,760 --> 00:05:32,000
Perhaps when he played the piano
in the brothels, his fingers moving
automatically,

66
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:35,280
he was able to dream,
compose, even read.

67
00:05:35,280 --> 00:05:37,480
He was a prodigious reader.

68
00:05:37,480 --> 00:05:42,600
In other words, the experience
may have strengthened him.

69
00:05:42,600 --> 00:05:45,920
MUSIC: "Three Sacred Choruses"
by Johannes Brahms

70
00:05:49,360 --> 00:05:51,840
Here, at St Michael's Church in
Hamburg,

71
00:05:51,840 --> 00:05:54,920
we can locate the roots
of Brahms's spiritual life.

72
00:05:54,920 --> 00:05:56,960
He was born and brought up
a Lutheran, of course, and

73
00:05:56,960 --> 00:06:02,880
he certainly took seriously Luther's
insistence on the importance of a
close personal study of the Bible.

74
00:06:02,880 --> 00:06:07,600
The Bible was a book that Brahms
knew extremely well and he used
as a resource all his life.

75
00:06:13,600 --> 00:06:16,640
Brahms never made any clear
statement about his beliefs,

76
00:06:16,640 --> 00:06:19,360
but seems to have been
a true agnostic,

77
00:06:19,360 --> 00:06:22,680
doubting some of the fundamental
doctrines of Christianity.

78
00:06:22,680 --> 00:06:24,720
Nothing, it was said, made him
angrier

79
00:06:24,720 --> 00:06:29,600
than when it was assumed he was
a conventional believer because
of his religious compositions.

80
00:06:29,600 --> 00:06:37,400
For him, the Bible was a source
of poetry, of morality,
and, perhaps, a source of wisdom.

81
00:06:37,400 --> 00:06:40,480
But not necessarily the word of God.

82
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:45,560
For the music of Brahms,

83
00:06:45,560 --> 00:06:50,560
Harry and the choir have come to
the Church of St Anne and St Agnes
in the City of London.

84
00:06:50,560 --> 00:06:55,480
It was built by Sir Christopher Wren
after the Great Fire, virtually
destroyed during the Blitz

85
00:06:55,480 --> 00:07:00,400
and rebuilt in the 1960s for the
Lutheran congregation of the city.

86
00:07:00,400 --> 00:07:04,400
MUSIC: "Ein Deutsches Requiem"
