87
00:07:04,400 --> 00:07:10,080
It's an appropriate location to
record some excerpts from the key
work of Brahms' early career -

88
00:07:10,080 --> 00:07:14,680
the free-thinking and deeply
humanistic German Requiem.

89
00:07:14,680 --> 00:07:18,560
What's fantastic about
the German Requiem

90
00:07:18,560 --> 00:07:20,560
is the whole story behind it.

91
00:07:20,560 --> 00:07:22,200
His whole personality behind it.

92
00:07:22,200 --> 00:07:26,560
The choice of texts which, for
me, is the most inspiring thing.

93
00:07:26,560 --> 00:07:30,280
They are so personal to him
and his beliefs.

94
00:07:30,280 --> 00:07:32,280
Ladies and gents,
can we have you please?

95
00:07:32,280 --> 00:07:34,920
Brahms, of course, sets his texts
in German,

96
00:07:34,920 --> 00:07:39,760
but because we've decided
to perform some of the extracts
in English translation,

97
00:07:39,760 --> 00:07:43,560
you might lose some of Brahms'
perfect setting
of the German syllables.

98
00:07:43,560 --> 00:07:47,200
But I do think you gain that
immediacy of understanding.

99
00:07:49,720 --> 00:07:58,840
# Blessed they

