Bible, which he knew so, so well,

112
00:09:14,520 --> 00:09:18,640
and making something that is very
personal, making his own statement.

113
00:09:18,640 --> 00:09:23,600
And that's what gives the piece
its eternal musical life.

114
00:09:25,680 --> 00:09:30,320
This is a very, very important
document

115
00:09:30,320 --> 00:09:36,360
because this is the handwriting
of eight-year-old Brahms.

116
00:09:36,360 --> 00:09:38,680
That's beautiful.
Isn't it beautiful?

117
00:09:44,200 --> 00:09:48,840
It is a letter to his teacher
saying, "I'm sorry,

118
00:09:48,840 --> 00:09:55,320
"I haven't practised enough
last year but I will practise more
next year."

119
00:09:55,320 --> 00:10:01,560
Because the teacher, Otto Cossel,
was always very critical
about his compositions.

120
00:10:01,560 --> 00:10:04,240
He wanted him to practise piano.

121
00:10:04,240 --> 00:10:08,480
This teacher saw him
becoming a piano virtuoso.

122
00:10:08,480 --> 00:10:11,600
But Brahms had other ideas.

123
00:10:11,600 --> 00:10:16,120
The Requiem is a substantial work,
over an hour long

124
00:10:16,120 --> 00:10:19,160
normally performed with a
huge orchestra and chorus.

125
00:10:19,160 --> 00:10:24,640
Harry has chosen to perform it
in this much less known
four-handed piano version.

126
00:10:39,400 --> 00:10:43,840
This was Brahms' own arrangement
at the request of his publisher.

127
00:10:43,840 --> 00:10:48,160
His publisher thought, in order
to get the work better known,
not only throughout Europe

128
00:10:48,160 --> 00:10:52,840
but also into England, let's make
an arrangement for a piano duet.

129
00:10:57,720 --> 00:11:01,120
We've actually got a Bosendorfer
piano of the same period,

130
00:11:01,120 --> 00:11:04,280
so there's a particular
quality to this Bosendorfer.

131
00:11:04,280 --> 00:11:08,720
It has a thundering bass
and a really eerie top register.

132
00:11:08,720 --> 00:11:11,400
Of course, you lose the colours
of the orchestra.

133
00:11:11,400 --> 00:11:16,440
But what you do benefit from
is that you get the vocal colours

134
00:11:16,440 --> 00:11:19,960
which can get so lost
in a big orchestral version.

135
00:11:21,320 --> 00:11:26,520
# Das Gras ist verdorret

136
00:11:29,800 --> 00:11:43,560
# Und die Blume abgefallen... #

137
00:11:45,320 --> 00:11:51,920
The picture of Brahms that I grew up
with is of an old man with a huge
beard, a huge white beard.

138
00:11:51,920 --> 00:11:56,800
Stout, twinkly but perhaps
a little bit aggressive.

139
00:11:56,800 --> 00:12:01,640
This picture is Brahms in his 30s,
around the time when he wrote
the German Requiem.

140
00:12:02,720 --> 00:12:05,480
He's actually quite a slight
young man.

141
00:12:05,480 --> 00:12:08,320
Although his face is getting
a little bit round.

142
00:12:09,400 --> 00:12:12,800
Very handsome.
Those famous piercing blue eyes.

143
00:12:12,800 --> 00:12:17,760
Above all, this picture,
to me, is a picture of
determination and of confidence.

144
00:12:17,760 --> 00:12:20,000
Look at that tight-set mouth.

145
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:23,120
I suspect that Brahms never
doubted his own gifts.

146
00:12:23,120 --> 00:12:25,400
I think Brahms knew
that he would make it,

147
00:12:25,400 --> 00:12:27,640
that he had something
important to say.

148
00:12:32,880 --> 00:12:36,000
In the spring of 1868,
the young, unknown composer

149
00:12:36,000 --> 00:12:40,400
had a version of his Requiem
ready for performance. And by his
own admission,

150
00:12:40,400 --> 00:12:42,400
feeling wretched with nerves,

151
00:12:42,400 --> 00:12:49,320
he made the journey
to the cathedral city of Bremen,
100 kilometres west of Hamburg.

152
00:12:51,600 --> 00:12:56,440
Brahms' worries weren't about
technical matters like
under-rehearsal.

153
00:12:56,440 --> 00:13:00,280
I suspect his anxiety had
deeper roots.

154
00:13:00,280 --> 00:13:05,200
The Requiem wasn't written on
commission. It was something Brahms
felt compelled to write

155
00:13:05,200 --> 00:13:10,120
and it is patently a deeply felt
statement of his faith,
whatever that might be.

156
00:13:10,120 --> 00:13:13,000
It was also
potentially controversial.

157
00:13:13,000 --> 00:13:17,560
A requiem performed
in a great cathedral on Good Friday

158
00:13:17,560 --> 00:13:20,800
and absolutely no mention of Christ.

159
00:13:23,560 --> 00:13:33,560
# Ich hoffe auf dich

160
00:13:26,000 --> 00:13:33,560
Ich hoffe auf dich

161
00:13:33,800 --> 00:13:37,360
# Auf dich

162
00:13:37,360 --> 00:13:43,320
# Ich hoffe auf dich

163
00:13:43,320 --> 00:13:50,680
# Ich hoffe auf dich

164
00:13:50,680 --> 00:13:55,920
# Der Gerechten Seelen sind
in Gottes Hand... #

165
00:13:55,920 --> 00:14:01,320
150 years after the event,
it's not difficult to imagine
why Brahms chose

166
00:14:01,320 --> 00:14:06,440
to unveil his masterpiece
at the Easter concert in this
beautiful, impressive cathedral.

167
00:14:06,440 --> 00:14:11,880
# ..Der Gerechten Seelen sind
in Gottes Hand

168
00:14:11,880 --> 00:14:14,760
# Und keine Qual ruhret sie an... #

169
00:14:14,760 --> 00:14:21,000
The work is carefully titled
Ein Deutsches Requiem -
A German Requiem.

170
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:26,880
German in this case referring to
the language sung rather than to
the composer's fellow countrymen.

171
00:14:26,880 --> 00:14:31,080
Brahms said he almost called it
A Human Requiem.

172
00:14:39,480 --> 00:14:44,720
As to Brahms' faith, well,
around the time of the first
performanceof the Requiem,

173
00:14:44,720 --> 00:14:47,240
he wrote his conductor, Rheintaler,
a letter.

174
00:14:47,240 --> 00:14:54,240
In it he said, "I could dispense
with passages like St John, 3.16."

175
00:14:54,240 --> 00:14:57,560
The passage he could dispense with
goes like this.

176
00:14:57,560 --> 00:15:01,160
"God so loved the world that he gave
his only begotten son

177
00:15:01,160 --> 00:15:07,000
"that whoever believes in him
should not perish
but have everlasting life."

178
00:15:07,000 --> 00:15:09,880
Brahms couldn't have made
himself clearer than that.

179
00:15:09,880 --> 00:15:17,280
# How lovely is thy dwelling place

180
00:15:17,280 --> 00:15:22,760
# O lord of Hosts

181
00:15:22,760 --> 00:15:27,080
# O lord of Hosts

182
00:15:31,120 --> 00:15:35,040
# Thy dwelling place

183
00:15:35,040 --> 00:15:44,800
# O lord of Hosts... #

184
00:15:44,800 --> 00:15:46,640
Brahms got away with it.

185
00:15:46,640 --> 00:15:51,760
His music was interspersed with
pieces by other composers - Tartini,
Bach, Schumann.

186
00:15:51,760 --> 00:15:57,120
Rheintaler cleverly suggested that
they should also perform Handel's
great aria from the Messiah,

187
00:15:57,120 --> 00:16:00,280
I Know That My Redeemer Liveth.

188
00:16:00,280 --> 00:16:04,600
Brahms didn't object and so Christ
did get a mention after all.

189
00:16:04,600 --> 00:16:12,960
# ..How lovely is thy dwelling place

190
00:16:12,960 --> 00:16:18,840
# O lord of Hosts... #

191
00:16:19,200 --> 00:16:25,040
Over 2,000 people came to listen,
including friends and other
influential musicians.

192
00:16:25,040 --> 00:16:29,880
Brahms, still in his thirties,
had finally arrived.

193
00:16:29,880 --> 00:16:35,640
# ..Yea, fainteth, it longeth,
