194
00:16:35,640 --> 00:16:43,160
# Yea, fainteth, yea, fainteth,
yea, fainteth

195
00:16:43,160 --> 00:16:51,880
# For the courts of the Lord... #

196
00:16:54,640 --> 00:16:59,680
The original idea for the Requiem
must have been closely bound up
with the death of his mother.

197
00:16:59,680 --> 00:17:02,240
The first mention of the peace
is in a letter

198
00:17:02,240 --> 00:17:06,640
written only a few months
after she died,
so she must have been on his mind.

199
00:17:06,640 --> 00:17:11,280
And in the sublime 5th movement,
which was held back from the
performancehere in Bremen,

200
00:17:11,280 --> 00:17:14,040
we find a promise
of maternal comfort.

201
00:17:15,640 --> 00:17:19,960
"Now is your time of sorrow
but I will see you again."

202
00:17:20,880 --> 00:17:27,640
# Ihr habt nun

203
00:17:27,640 --> 00:17:36,880
# Traurigkeit... #

204
00:17:37,920 --> 00:17:41,600
The movement is a
bit of a stand-alone movement.

205
00:17:41,600 --> 00:17:44,320
It's a totally different
atmosphere from the other pieces.

206
00:17:44,320 --> 00:17:48,600
It's very...comforting. I think
that's the main word. Reassuring.

207
00:17:48,600 --> 00:17:54,480
And I was told by a wonderful singing
teacher who said you have to imagine
yourself as an angel,

208
00:17:54,480 --> 00:17:58,080
or possibly once you've had children,
you imagine yourself as a mother

209
00:17:58,080 --> 00:18:00,120
and that's certainly the way I think
about it

210
00:18:00,120 --> 00:18:02,760
when I'm singing this reassuring,
comforting presence

211
00:18:02,760 --> 00:18:06,560
that's going to heal all the wounds
and badness in people's
struggle through life.

212
00:18:06,560 --> 00:18:11,400
# ..Ich will euch wieder sehen

213
00:18:11,400 --> 00:18:21,040
