215
00:18:35,320 --> 00:18:38,720
A requiem mass for the dead, missa
pro defunctis,

216
00:18:38,720 --> 00:18:43,000
is normally composed for
the performance at funerals
or memorial services.

217
00:18:43,000 --> 00:18:47,720
The word Requiem comes
from the first line of
the standard Latin text.

218
00:18:47,720 --> 00:18:50,240
"Requiem eternam dona eis, Domine."

219
00:18:50,240 --> 00:18:53,240
Grant them eternal rest, O Lord.

220
00:18:55,240 --> 00:18:57,280
Brahms produced something different.

221
00:18:57,280 --> 00:19:03,160
A concert requiem, or with his
piano version, even a domestic one.

222
00:19:03,160 --> 00:19:11,080
# ..Ich will euch wieder sehen... #

223
00:19:11,080 --> 00:19:17,160
Brahms was only 33,
but death had already cast
its shadow onto his soul.

224
00:19:17,160 --> 00:19:22,280
To uncover what I think is the
earliest and deepest layer of
inspiration for the German Requiem,

225
00:19:22,280 --> 00:19:25,880
we have to turn the clock back
15 years.

226
00:19:25,880 --> 00:19:30,520
Whilst celebrating his 20th birthday
hiking down the Rhine,

227
00:19:30,520 --> 00:19:35,640
Brahms passed through Dusseldorf
and there he had an encounter
that would change his life.

228
00:19:38,360 --> 00:19:42,920
Imagine the young Johannes, who was
on holiday, deciding on the spur of
the moment

229
00:19:42,920 --> 00:19:45,760
to come here to this house
to call on one of his heroes,

230
00:19:45,760 --> 00:19:50,280
the composer Robert Schumann
and his wife Clara, the formidable
piano virtuoso.

231
00:19:50,280 --> 00:19:54,480
He'd never met them before so he
must have been extremely nervous.
He knocked on the door.

232
00:19:58,200 --> 00:20:02,080
And they were both out. However, he
came back the next day, tried again.

233
00:20:04,280 --> 00:20:07,320
And Robert Schumann
answered the door.

234
00:20:43,560 --> 00:20:45,480
This is the first floor
of the house

235
00:20:45,480 --> 00:20:51,400
so it could very well have been
the place where the piano was and
where music was played.

236
00:20:51,400 --> 00:20:55,400
So we can imagine Brahms coming
here, his heart in his mouth,

237
00:20:56,440 --> 00:21:01,640
to meet the great composer
and his formidable wife.

238
00:21:01,640 --> 00:21:05,080
So Brahms sat down and played

239
00:21:05,080 --> 00:21:07,800
one of his own piano pieces.

240
00:21:19,200 --> 00:21:21,000
At the end of the session,

241
00:21:21,000 --> 00:21:27,520
Robert Schumann turned round and
said to the young man, "You and
I understand each other."

242
00:21:29,840 --> 00:21:33,600
The Schumanns were German music's
most celebrated couple.

243
00:21:33,600 --> 00:21:35,800
Always on the lookout for emerging
talent,

244
00:21:35,800 --> 00:21:42,160
they now publicly proclaimed
the unknown composer, scarcely
out of his teens, as a genius.

245
00:21:45,840 --> 00:21:49,360
Brahms, Robert declared,
was the chosen one,

246
00:21:49,360 --> 00:21:53,840
whilst Clara wrote that he had
come as if sent directly from God.

247
00:21:53,840 --> 00:21:57,200
This must have had a huge impact
on Brahms's self confidence

248
00:21:57,200 --> 00:22:01,600
but their friendship was to be
cruelly cut short after only a year,

249
00:22:01,600 --> 00:22:05,160
when Robert Schumann was afflicted
with mental illness.

250
00:22:07,200 --> 00:22:09,960
It was a descent into hell.

251
00:22:09,960 --> 00:22:13,720
He was seized by violent attacks
of hallucinations

252
00:22:13,720 --> 00:22:20,240
and, with tragic irony, he was
tortured by strange, unearthly music
and nightmarish mocking voices.

253
00:22:25,680 --> 00:22:27,560
Finally he could stand it no longer.

254
00:22:27,560 --> 00:22:34,280
One night he ran from his house in
his dressing gown, came to a bridge,
and threw himself into the Rhine.

255
00:22:34,280 --> 00:22:38,240
He didn't kill himself. He was
dragged from the river by some
fishermen

256
00:22:38,240 --> 00:22:40,160
and asked to be taken to an asylum.

257
00:22:44,120 --> 00:22:49,440
Two and a half years later,
the great Romantic composer
Robert Schumann was dead.

258
00:22:50,400 --> 00:22:55,760
His wife Clara and his
young protege, Brahms,
were stricken with grief.

259
00:22:56,720 --> 00:23:02,480
A decade on, Brahms still felt it
as an enduring and agonising loss.

260
00:23:04,560 --> 00:23:09,560
In the 6th movement of the German
Requiem, there's an anger that was
boiling up in him.

261
00:23:09,560 --> 00:23:13,880
Brahms really was crying out to God,

262
00:23:13,880 --> 00:23:21,640
"Why have you taken
Schumann away from us, away from
me and the musical world?"

263
00:23:21,640 --> 00:23:26,880
Brahms just erupts. It's really
incredibly exciting music.

264
00:23:27,200 --> 00:23:34,040
# Der Tod ist verschlungen
in den Sieg

265
