00:24:49,040 --> 00:24:57,760
# Wo ist dein Sieg?

284
00:24:58,680 --> 00:25:03,480
Harry, there are so many
interior contemplative moments
in the Requiem.

285
00:25:03,480 --> 00:25:05,440
This is not one of them, is it?

286
00:25:05,440 --> 00:25:08,320
This is hugely, obviously dramatic.

287
00:25:08,320 --> 00:25:11,120
Dramatic, almost angry at times. Yes.

288
00:25:11,120 --> 00:25:16,480
I mean, I feel it suddenly
gets the choir to sing this amazing
legato, rich harmonies going around.

289
00:25:16,480 --> 00:25:19,240
It's almost the opera
he didn't write, it seems.

290
00:25:19,240 --> 00:25:23,360
The choir are now singing at
absolute at full pelt, aren't they?

291
00:25:23,360 --> 00:25:24,880
Yes.

292
00:25:24,880 --> 00:25:32,640
# Holle, wo ist dein Sieg?

293
00:25:32,640 --> 00:25:35,400
# Holle, wo ist dein Sieg? #

294
00:25:35,400 --> 00:25:39,040
They're crashing away. Amazing.
Fabulous, absolutely fabulous.

295
00:25:39,040 --> 00:25:44,040
It's a marvellous bit to sing,
isn't it? This release... It expands.
..you can be expansive.

296
00:25:44,040 --> 00:25:48,840
It's hope, isn't it?
It's a positive device,
isn't it, that lovely ascension?

297
00:25:48,840 --> 00:25:51,480
The whole Requiem is a requiem
of hope.

298
00:25:57,400 --> 00:26:00,720
Out of his personal experiences
and emotions,

299
00:26:00,720 --> 00:26:05,800
his very human anger and grief,
Brahms had produced a masterpiece.

300
00:26:05,800 --> 00:26:11,360
Beautiful choral music with
sincere sentiments that resonated
with audiences and performers

301
00:26:11,360 --> 00:26:14,600
no matter what their faith
or religious beliefs.

302
00:26:22,160 --> 00:26:25,280
After playing through the
four-handed piano arrangement,

303
00:26:25,280 --> 00:26:28,040
Clara Schumann wrote
to the composer,

304
00:26:28,040 --> 00:26:35,040
"This is a truly tremendous work of
art and it moves the entire being
like nothing else before it."

305
00:26:39,000 --> 00:26:42,040
Within five years, the work
had been sung across Germany

306
00:26:42,040 --> 00:26:46,040
and had had performances in Vienna,
Paris and London.

307
00:26:46,040 --> 00:26:54,440
# Blessed, blessed, blessed

308
00:26:54,440 --> 00:27:02,440
# Blessed are the dead

309
00:27:02,440 --> 00:27:05,680
# The dead... #

310
00:27:05,680 --> 00:27:09,040
Brahms's Requiem is one of the most
challenging pieces to sing.

311
00:27:09,040 --> 00:27:12,160
I think you need immense stamina
to get through it.

312
00:27:12,160 --> 00:27:13,880
Not just vocally, but emotionally.

313
00:27:13,880 --> 00:27:17,520
The singers have to find the depth
within themselves and the strength

314
00:27:17,520 --> 00:27:21,840
to cover all the places
Brahms wanted to take you.

315
00:27:21,840 --> 00:27:26,120
When you have a whole performance of
it in one go, I think the audience
is very often shocked

316
00:27:26,120 --> 00:27:28,160
to feel the immensity of emotion.

317
00:27:28,160 --> 00:27:36,640
# From henceforth... #

318
00:27:45,600 --> 00:27:48,400
It's a remarkable achievement.

319
00:27:48,400 --> 00:27:51,840
The Requiem made Brahms'
name and reputation.

320
00:27:51,840 --> 00:27:56,480
And though still a young man,
he now settled into his role
as a major composer.

321
00:27:56,480 --> 00:27:59,760
He moved to Vienna,
the European capital of music.

322
00:27:59,760 --> 00:28:06,040
And while there, he created some
of the 19th century's greatest and
most deeply felt symphonic music.

323
00:28:06,040 --> 00:28:13,000
And it was the symphony
that drew our second composer,
Anton Bruckner, to Vienna as well.

324
00:28:13,000 --> 00:28:17,920
Despite some similarities,
these were two men from very
different spiritual backgrounds.

325
00:28:17,920 --> 00:28:21,560
In contrast to Brahms' upbringing
within the Protestant tradition,

326
00:28:21,560 --> 00:28:24,280
Anton Bruckner was
a devout Roman Catholic.

327
00:28:24,280 --> 00:28:27,240
To explore some of his magnificent
sacred music,

328
00:28:27,240 --> 00:28:32,400
Harry Christopher's choir,
The Sixteen, have chosen to visit
Dowey Abbey,

329
00:28:32,400 --> 00:28:34,320
a monastery in Berkshire.

330
00:28:38,280 --> 00:28:42,720
Here, the abbey church
possesses both the appropriate
devotional atmosphere

331
00:28:42,720 --> 00:28:47,320
and a generous acoustic that allows
Bruckner's unique voice to be heard.

332
00:28:47,320 --> 00:28:55,920
# ..Dona eis, Domine

333
00:28:58,120 --> 00:29:19,920
# Et lux perpetua luceat eis... #

334
00:29:19,920 --> 00:29:24,840
This is Anton Bruckner photographed
shortly before his death in 1896,

335
00:29:24,840 --> 00:29:28,440
when, after a lifetime of obscurity
and failure,

336
00:29:28,440 --> 00:29:33,680
he'd finally been recognised as one
of the great composers of his age.

337
00:29:33,680 --> 00:29:37,400
During his years of struggle, it
was the Church

338
00:29:37,400 --> 00:29:44,360
and the composition of church music
that he turns to time and time again
for consolation.

339
00:29:45,400 --> 00:29:52,560
# In die illa

340
00:29:52,560 --> 00:30:02,040
# Illa tremenda

341
00:30:05,640 --> 00:30:15,400
# Quando coeli movendi... #

342
00:30:15,400 --> 00:30:20,360
The first of 11 children,
Anton was born in Ansfelden,

343
00:30:20,360 --> 00:30:23,520
a village hidden away in a
forgotten part of upper Austria.

344
00:30:23,520 --> 00:30:26,480
The community was conservative,
even reactionary,

345
00:30:26,480 --> 00:30:31,040
untroubled by any new ideas being
hatched in the big world outside.

346
00:30:31,040 --> 00:30:35,040
For a child born here, expectations
cannot have been very great.

347
00:30:36,040 --> 00:30:43,040
# ..Judicare saeculum

348
00:30:43,680 --> 00:30:49,120
# Per ignem.... #

349
00:30:49,120 --> 00:30:53,680
Like so many Austrians of the time,
the Bruckners were pious people.

350
00:30:53,680 --> 00:30:58,760
The most important legacy
of Anton's upbringing
was his unshakeable faith.

351
00:30:58,760 --> 00:31:02,520
Even when, in later life, he may
have had doubts about his music,

352
00:31:02,520 --> 00:31:06,920
he never lost trust in his God
and the Roman Catholic Church.

353
00:31:14,680 --> 00:31:18,480
Anton's father died when
he was only 12 years old.

354
00:31:18,480 --> 00:31:24,440
On the very same day,
his mother brought him here, to
the great monastery of St Florian.

355
00:31:24,440 --> 00:31:27,680
And begged the prior
to take him on as a chorister.

356
00:31:27,680 --> 00:31:32,120
This was an act
not so much of callousness,
as of rigorous good sense.

357
00:31:32,120 --> 00:31:37,640
Despite his age -
Anton was a little too old -
the Prior agreed to take him on.

358
00:31:37,640 --> 00:31:40,880
His mother was not to know
that she'd introduced her son

359
00:31:40,880 --> 00:31:45,280
to the place that was to be,
for the rest of his life,
his spiritual home.

360
00:32:00,720 --> 00:32:04,640
In this beautiful and ancient
establishment of work and prayer,

361
00:32:04,640 --> 00:32:09,240
Bruckner was protected from the
outside world.
First, as a boy chorister,

362
00:32:09,240 --> 00:32:12,880
then, in his twenties,
as the church organist.

363
00:32:12,880 --> 00:32:16,240
He felt he had a calling
to serve God

364
00:32:16,240 --> 00:32:20,840
as a musician
and as a composer of sacred music.

365
00:32:24,880 --> 00:32:28,840
There it is, the organ
that Bruckner played while he
was at the monastery.

366
00:32:30,680 --> 00:32:32,200
It's rather impressive.

367
00:33:01,680 --> 00:33:03,520
Klaus, thank you very much for that.

368
00:33:03,520 --> 00:33:06,120
So, you were playing Bruckner's
organ.

369
00:33:06,120 --> 00:33:09,440
Yes, this is the organ

370
00:33:09,440 --> 00:33:13,720
which inspired Bruckner
for his work, his composing.

371
00:33:13,720 --> 00:33:16,040
It's not the original console.

372
00:33:16,040 --> 00:33:20,880
You can see it's a modern piece
installed in 1951.

373
00:33:20,880 --> 00:33:25,480
But the rest of the organ, the
pipes, would have been what he knew?
Yes. That's right.

374
00:33:25,480 --> 00:33:30,640
The case is original,
with more than 7,300 pipes.

375
00:33:30,640 --> 00:33:32,200
That's a big, big organ.

376
00:33:32,200 --> 00:33:36,360
And his duties would be to play
at every service?

377
00:33:36,360 --> 00:33:39,160
I think he played a lot of services.

378
00:33:39,160 --> 00:33:43,320
He used to, we know, improvise.

379
00:33:43,320 --> 00:33:46,360
Improvising was the speciality
of Anton Bruckner.

380
00:33:46,360 --> 00:33:52,880
We know he did compose few pieces
for the organ because he was a big
improviser.

381
00:33:52,880 --> 00:33:55,120
And a very good improviser.

