417
00:37:17,200 --> 00:37:19,240
Oh, the labour of
love over all of this.

418
00:37:21,600 --> 00:37:23,360
Just fantastically neat.

419
00:37:27,040 --> 00:37:31,920
This almost obsessive neatness
gave me an insight
into the dogged dedication

420
00:37:31,920 --> 00:37:36,440
that Bruckner brought his calling
as a composer in the service of God.

421
00:37:38,160 --> 00:37:42,040
He'd only just turned 30
and the writing of this solemn Mass

422
00:37:42,040 --> 00:37:44,680
proved to be a turning
point in his development.

423
00:37:44,680 --> 00:37:50,320
It was the last composition he dared
to commit to paper for five years.

424
00:37:53,480 --> 00:37:56,360
Perhaps, realising
he still had much to learn

425
00:37:56,360 --> 00:38:00,560
and that he needed to grow as a
musician, he decided to move on.

426
00:38:02,520 --> 00:38:06,520
When he was offered the post of
organist here at Linz Cathedral,

427
00:38:06,520 --> 00:38:10,440
he was told he looked a little
shabby and might have to
tidy himself up a bit.

428
00:38:10,440 --> 00:38:13,920
His playing was magnificent and, of
course, he was offered the job.

429
00:38:16,360 --> 00:38:18,360
Bruckner hesitated.

430
00:38:18,360 --> 00:38:21,960
He managed to persuade
the monastery to keep his old job
open for two years

431
00:38:21,960 --> 00:38:26,400
and only when he had
that reassurance
would he take up his new post.

432
00:38:26,400 --> 00:38:32,320
Now that he was a fully fledged
professional musician,
the hard work could begin.

433
00:38:37,600 --> 00:38:42,760
Over the next five years,
instead of composing,
he decided to take lessons -

434
00:38:42,760 --> 00:38:48,320
a correspondence course with a
Viennese teacher, Simon Sechter,
in harmony and counterpoint.

435
00:38:48,320 --> 00:38:53,520
In fact, he worked so hard that
his teacher was impelled to write
him a letter which said,

436
00:38:53,520 --> 00:38:59,000
"I do implore you to take care of
yourself and allow yourself
sufficient relaxation."

437
00:38:59,000 --> 00:39:05,200
# Locus iste

438
00:39:05,200 --> 00:39:11,240
# A Deo factus est... #

439
00:39:11,240 --> 00:39:16,400
If anything,
Bruckner's love for the church was
becoming even more intense.

440
00:39:16,400 --> 00:39:20,640
This motet, written for the
dedication of a chapel in Linz,

441
00:39:20,640 --> 00:39:23,560
seems to translate this love
directly into music.

442
00:39:25,160 --> 00:39:32,400
Locus iste a Deo factus est,
inaestimabile sacramentum
irreprehensibilis est.

443
00:39:32,400 --> 00:39:38,880
This dwelling is God's handiwork,
a mystery beyond price
that cannot be spoken against.

444
00:39:38,880 --> 00:39:47,720
# Inaestimabile sacramentum

445
00:39:47,720 --> 00:39:59,040
# Inaestimabile sacramentum... #

446
00:39:59,040 --> 00:40:03,280
His Catholicism speaks through maybe
in the simplicity of what he does

447
00:40:03,280 --> 00:40:07,160
but also in the waves of
sounds and emotion.

448
00:40:07,160 --> 00:40:11,000
Even something as simple as Locus
Iste, starts so quietly, so gently

449
00:40:11,000 --> 00:40:13,560
but it goes through
this massive sound in the middle.

450
00:40:13,560 --> 00:40:15,760
It really feels like opening a
door into his religious landscape.

451
00:40:15,760 --> 00:40:30,960
# Irreprehensibilis est... #

452
00:40:30,960 --> 00:40:34,600
After 10 years in Linz,
Bruckner, aged 42,

453
00:40:34,600 --> 00:40:38,360
suffered a severe nervous breakdown
and was sent to a sanatorium.

454
00:40:38,360 --> 00:40:44,880
# ..A Deo factus est... #

455
00:40:44,880 --> 00:40:49,720
He described it as a condition of
utter degradation and loneliness.

456
00:40:49,720 --> 00:40:52,360
It drove him to the edge of suicide.

457
00:40:52,360 --> 00:40:55,080
Although he recovered, this time,

458
00:40:55,080 --> 00:41:00,640
it left a legacy of anxiety
and fear and he decided
he had to leave Linz.

459
00:41:05,680 --> 00:41:10,280
For the rest of his long life,
he earned his living as a teacher
of music while struggling

460
00:41:10,280 --> 00:41:17,200
to build his reputation as a
symphonic composer in the capital
of the Austrian Empire, Vienna.

461
00:41:19,280 --> 00:41:25,240
The apartment that was Bruckner's
home for nigh on two decades is now
a suite in the Hotel de France.

462
00:41:25,240 --> 00:41:27,600
Guten Abend.

463
00:41:29,920 --> 00:41:36,200
By the 1870s, both Brahms and
Bruckner had made their homes
here in the Austrian capital.

464
00:41:36,200 --> 00:41:41,240
Brahms, now a musical celebrity
thanks to the German Requiem,
was in his mid-30.

465
00:41:41,240 --> 00:41:46,160
Bruckner, around 10 years older,
was still working in semi-obscurity.

466
00:41:51,080 --> 00:41:55,800
So, I'll be sleeping tonight
in Anton Bruckner's room.

467
00:41:55,800 --> 00:42:00,520
It feels slightly odd, when we've
lost so much of the physical world
that these two composers knew,

468
00:42:00,520 --> 00:42:04,200
to be here,
somewhere quite so intimate.

469
00:42:04,200 --> 00:42:06,320
I don't expect to
see any ghosts but...

470
00:42:07,840 --> 00:42:09,520
I do expect a good night's sleep.

471
00:42:12,760 --> 00:42:14,920
MUSIC: Symphony No. 4, 3rd movement
by Bruckner

472
00:42:21,880 --> 00:42:26,080
For both composers,
Vienna was the ultimate test.

473
00:42:27,120 --> 00:42:32,000
It could lay claim to be the
European capital of music,
indeed of the arts.

474
00:42:32,000 --> 00:42:35,560
And any German-speaking composer
must have dreamt of making it here.

475
00:42:37,680 --> 00:42:41,680
Brahms rented two rooms
here in Karlsgasse.

476
00:42:41,680 --> 00:42:45,760
A friend described them as a sort
of place suitable for a student,

477
00:42:45,760 --> 00:42:50,360
a minor civil servant,
or a salesman starting out in trade.

478
00:42:50,360 --> 00:42:52,680
They were, frankly, shabby.

479
00:42:52,680 --> 00:42:56,960
And in Viennese eyes, at least,
not remotely appropriate
for a great artist.

480
00:42:56,960 --> 00:43:00,840
But then, that was typical
of the man. He was a bundle
of contradictions -

481
00:43:00,840 --> 00:43:02,840
mean-spirited, yet tender.

482
00:43:02,840 --> 00:43:05,080
Progressive, reactionary.

483
00:43:05,080 --> 00:43:10,520
He once boasted that he could find
any passage in his Bible instantly,
even in the dark.

484
00:43:12,880 --> 00:43:16,240
Like Bruckner,
he was still writing sacred music.

485
00:43:18,080 --> 00:43:25,040
Above all, he was drawn to the bleak
agony and the harsh questions
of the Book of Job.

486
00:43:25,040 --> 00:43:30,640
# Warum

487
00:43:38,520 --> 00:43:41,280
# Warum ist das Licht... #

488
00:43:41,280 --> 00:43:44,360
"Wherefore is light given to him
that is in misery,

489
00:43:44,360 --> 00:43:49,040
"and life unto the bitter in soul,
which long for death
but it cometh not?

490
00:43:49,040 --> 00:43:53,200
"Why is light given
to a man whose way is hid

491
00:43:53,200 --> 00:43:56,400
"and whom God hath hedged in?"

492
00:44:13,920 --> 00:44:16,680
If A German Requiem had
promised comfort

493
00:44:16,680 --> 00:44:19,200
to the living in the presence of
death,

494
00:44:19,200 --> 00:44:24,360
then this motet, with its cry of
despair and subsequent sense of
stoic resignation,

495
00:44:24,360 --> 00:44:30,040
offers another
individual response to the deaths
that had clouded Brahms' life.

496
00:44:40,720 --> 00:44:43,960
It was inevitable
that Brahms and Bruckner would meet.

497
00:44:43,960 --> 00:44:48,920
But surprisingly, it was neither
in the concert hall, nor the church.

498
00:44:48,920 --> 00:44:55,040
Our two composers had a taste
for cold draught Pilsner.

499
00:44:55,040 --> 00:45:01,880
And the best beer in Vienna could
be found at an eating house called
Zum Roten Igel, the Red Hedgehog.

500
00:45:01,880 --> 00:45:05,160
The place range with
the sounds of fierce arguments

501
00:45:05,160 --> 00:45:10,040
between various cliques
proselytising for their
chosen musical champions.

502
00:45:11,120 --> 00:45:16,960
Accounts of the two masters
meeting bristled with discomfort
and suppressed aggression.

503
00:45:16,960 --> 00:45:24,200
Brahms privately thought Bruckner
a deluded fool, ruined by priests,
his music was a swindle.

504
00:45:24,200 --> 00:45:30,320
Bruckner, meanwhile,
dismissed Brahms as a craftsman,
not a composer.

505
00:45:30,320 --> 00:45:36,400
Danke schon. In the best description
we have of one of their encounters,
Brahms is cold and dismissive,

506
00:45:36,400 --> 00:45:44,160
whilst Bruckner, always polite,
sometimes even obsequious, scuttles
off to get his great rival a beer.

507
00:45:46,840 --> 00:45:49,960
Nice and cold.

508
00:45:49,960 --> 00:45:54,360
# Ecce sacerdos magnus

509
00:45:54,360 --> 00:46:00,760
# Ecce sacerdos magnus

510
00:46:00,760 --> 00:46:03,360
# Ecce sacerdos

511
00:46:03,360 --> 00:46:14,640
# Magnus. #

512
00:46:15,920 --> 00:46:21,160
This is Bruckner's rather
bird-like face with, in this case,
quite a beady stare.

513
00:46:23,160 --> 00:46:26,680
He never sported a beard,
unlike more fashionable men
of his time,

514
00:46:26,680 --> 00:46:30,640
and he was mocked by
the sophisticated Viennese
for his odd behaviour.

515
00:46:33,640 --> 00:46:36,560
And is there an indication
here too, in his expression,

516
00:46:36,560 --> 00:46:41,440
of the insecurities he often
felt about the wider world
beyond the safety of the Church?

517
00:46:46,840 --> 00:46:49,280
Bruckner's writing is so of him

518
00:46:49,280 --> 00:46:51,240
and his beliefs.

519
00:46:51,240 --> 00:46:54,840
You see that same
fervour and personality

520
00:46:54,840 --> 00:46:57,400
and love of his church
coming through.

521
00:46:58,640 --> 00:47:03,960
His sheer power, emotion,
is so profound.

522
00:47:03,960 --> 00:47:08,200
He has put so much of his own
personality into the music.

523
00:47:09,800 --> 00:47:13,960
VOICES GRADUALLY RISE
IN A LOUD CRESCENDO

524
00:47:23,800 --> 00:47:26,000
It's loud, isn't it?
It is very loud.

525
00:47:26,000 --> 00:47:28,920
It's the impact,
the cumulative impact. Fantastic.

526
00:47:28,920 --> 00:47:31,840
Can you tell me how Bruckner
achieves his effects in this?

527
00:47:31,840 --> 00:47:36,680
In this particular piece,
he uses a sort of refrain, really,
he uses it three times in all.

528
00:47:36,680 --> 00:47:41,840
And he builds it up from a succession
of root position chords. The simplest
chords you can get. Absolutely, yes.

529
00:47:41,840 --> 00:47:46,880
He starts in E major, then goes
to A minor, right through, G major,
E flat, ending up in C major.

530
00:47:46,880 --> 00:47:51,600
He goes right through
the progression. We're going to sing
that progression of chords.

531
00:47:52,680 --> 00:47:58,160
THEY SING THROUGH
THE CHORD PROGRESSION

532
00:48:15,080 --> 00:48:18,200
That's fantastic, and they don't
quite go where you'd expect them to.

533
00:48:18,200 --> 00:48:19,880
There are a couple
of surprises in there.

534
00:48:19,880 --> 00:48:25,200
And at the beginning, he just has the
sopranos and altos with the organ,
and the men are with the trombones,

535
00:48:25,200 --> 00:48:28,160
until we get to this fantastic
F major, C major finish.

536
00:48:28,160 --> 00:48:31,720
Everything comes together,
it's quite brilliant. Let's hear it.

537
00:48:31,720 --> 00:48:36,760
THEY SING, REPEATING
THE SECTION IN FULL

538
00:49:18,120 --> 00:49:22,400
The power and originality
of Bruckner's sacred music
proved to be no barrier

539
00:49:22,400 --> 00:49:26,400
to its ready acceptance as music
for worship in the Catholic Church.

540
00:49:26,400 --> 00:49:31,520
But for his secular orchestral
music, it was a different story.

541
00:49:31,520 --> 00:49:37,120
The musical establishment's
response to his earliest symphonies
was criticism and indifference.

542
00:49:43,480 --> 00:49:46,880
Then, after 20 years of
misunderstanding, his 7th Symphony,

543
00:49:46,880 --> 00:49:52,920
as vast and ambitious as a
cathedral, found an audience.

544
00:49:58,120 --> 00:50:03,120
But the recognition Anton Bruckner
craved had come almost too late.

545
00:50:03,120 --> 00:50:07,640
As he grew older,
he was unable to hide his
increasingly obsessive behaviour.

546
00:50:07,640 --> 00:50:12,640
What started out simply
as counting bars in music,
erupted into numeromania.

547
00:50:12,640 --> 00:50:18,800
He would count everything,
grains of sand, stars in the sky,
leaves on a tree, even the pearls

548
00:50:18,800 --> 00:50:24,480
set on to ladies' dresses,
rigorously returning to his starting
point when he lost his tally.

549
00:50:24,480 --> 00:50:29,480
And his prayers, always strictly
observed, became ever more feverish.

550
00:50:35,160 --> 00:50:42,520
For Bruckner, every experience was
intense and absolute, and every act
of composition was an act of prayer.

551
00:50:42,520 --> 00:50:46,880
In the Roman Catholic faith, the
Virgin Mary is a bringer of comfort.

552
00:50:46,880 --> 00:50:54,320
And in his profound devotion to her,
Bruckner set the text, Ave Maria,
three times.

553
00:50:54,320 --> 00:51:03,240
# Benedicta tu in mulieribus

554
00:51:03,240 --> 00:51:09,640
# Et benedictus

555
00:51:09,640 --> 00:51:18,600
# Fructus ventris tui. #

556
00:51:18,600 --> 00:51:24,120
In his final year,
Bruckner, now frail and with
a mind wandering alarmingly,

557
00:51:24,120 --> 00:51:28,360
was offered a place to
live by the Emperor himself,
here at the Belvedere Palace.

558
00:51:28,360 --> 00:51:33,600
He must have felt extremely proud
that a man from a small village
in Upper Austria

559
00:51:33,600 --> 00:51:36,120
had been deemed worthy
of such an honour.

560
00:51:37,960 --> 00:51:43,440
# Jesus...! #

561
00:51:44,240 --> 00:51:48,320
His last day start unexceptionally.

562
00:51:48,320 --> 00:51:51,800
He worked in the morning on
the finale of his 9th Symphony,

563
00:51:51,800 --> 00:51:55,480
then in the early afternoon, he went
for a stroll in the public gardens.

564
00:51:55,480 --> 00:52:00,080
He then returned to his small
apartment where he died.

565
00:52:09,120 --> 00:52:14,760
The funeral of Anton Bruckner
took place on 4th October 1896

566
00:52:14,760 --> 00:52:18,520
in Vienna's most beautiful church,
the Karlskirche.

567
00:52:21,480 --> 00:52:23,680
The church was packed.

568
00:52:23,680 --> 00:52:26,320
When Brahms came
to pay his respects,

569
00:52:26,320 --> 00:52:30,560
an attendant assured him that, yes,
they could probably squeeze him in.

570
00:52:30,560 --> 00:52:34,720
But he hesitated,
and then turned to leave.

571
00:52:34,720 --> 00:52:40,120
He was heard to mutter,
"Never mind, soon my coffin."

572
00:53:04,400 --> 00:53:08,760
Bruchner's body was brought home
to the monastery of St Florian,

573
00:53:08,760 --> 00:53:15,400
and laid to rest directly underneath
the great organ on which he had
learned to play and to compose.

574
00:53:15,400 --> 00:53:18,040
Once, when he was asked what
he might say to his God

575
00:53:18,040 --> 00:53:21,000
if required to give an account
of his life here on Earth,

576
00:53:21,000 --> 00:53:27,120
Bruckner allegedly replied,
"I will present to him the score
of some of my work,

577
00:53:27,120 --> 00:53:30,880
"and he will judge me mercifully."

578
00:53:41,760 --> 00:53:54,320
# Amen. #

579
00:53:54,320 --> 00:54:01,000
Johannes Brahms was only
63 when Bruckner died,
but his life too was nearly over.

580
00:54:03,760 --> 00:54:07,960
If Bruckner was assured
of the immortality of his soul,

581
00:54:07,960 --> 00:54:13,040
then Brahms was assured
of this - that his immortality
lay in his work.

582
00:54:13,040 --> 00:54:16,520
# Mit Fried und Freud

583
00:54:16,520 --> 00:54:23,120
# Ich fahr dahin

584
00:54:23,120 --> 00:54:26,280
# In Gottes

585
00:54:26,280 --> 00:54:32,400
# Willen

586
00:54:33,520 --> 00:54:37,560
# Getrost ist mir

587
00:54:37,560 --> 00:54:41,640
# Mein Herz

588
00:54:41,640 --> 00:54:44,720
# Und Sinn. #

589
00:54:46,280 --> 00:54:49,560
He composed less and less
during those final years,

590
00:54:49,560 --> 00:54:54,280
and inevitably friends
that he had cared for and
members of his family died.

591
00:54:55,920 --> 00:55:00,880
He must have been hit terribly
hard in 1896 when he heard of
the death of Clara Schumann.

592
00:55:03,000 --> 00:55:09,360
She had been his greatest friend
ever since that first meeting
in Dusseldorf 40 years earlier.

593
00:55:09,360 --> 00:55:15,640
Now, the last link with
Brahms's inspiration and hero,
Robert Schumann, was gone.

594
00:55:27,960 --> 00:55:32,360
His last composition was
this set of organ preludes

595
00:55:32,360 --> 00:55:35,360
based on chorales that he must
have heard in church as a child.

596
00:55:35,360 --> 00:55:37,720
There were found at his
apartment after his death.

597
00:55:37,720 --> 00:55:40,920
Perhaps he would never
have published them himself.

598
00:55:48,080 --> 00:55:54,320
Simple and sweetly melancholic,
they seem to look back to the
happier days of Brahms's youth.

599
00:55:56,000 --> 00:56:01,320
It's kind of difficult to work out
exactly what he was hoping to achieve
with these chorale preludes,

600
00:56:01,320 --> 00:56:07,320
but I think that it was just a sort
of homage to Robert Schumann and
Clara, and it's the sort of thing

601
00:56:07,320 --> 00:56:09,000
that people do in later life,

602
00:56:09,000 --> 00:56:12,880
which is to go back to something
that they feel has been left undone.

603
00:56:12,880 --> 00:56:15,080
That may well have been it.

604
00:56:18,080 --> 00:56:22,600
It took a long time for Brahms
to admit he was ill with cancer.

605
00:56:22,600 --> 00:56:26,360
But, inevitably, the time came
when he had to take to his bed,

606
00:56:26,360 --> 00:56:33,320
and finally, on 3rd April 1897,
Johannes Brahms died.

607
00:56:51,520 --> 00:56:54,640
This is where Brahms
was finally laid to rest.

608
00:56:54,640 --> 00:56:58,280
In what he himself
had called a sacred place.

609
00:56:58,280 --> 00:57:03,640
Next to his friend Johann Strauss,
and near Schubert and Beethoven.

610
00:57:03,640 --> 00:57:07,360
A great composer amongst his peers.

611
00:57:10,960 --> 00:57:14,520
MUSIC: Requiem, Op. 48,
Johannes Brahms

612
00:57:31,920 --> 00:57:36,200
For Brahms, life was a struggle,
something to be endured.

613
00:57:36,200 --> 00:57:41,760
His music doesn't seem to have been
written in praise of God, nor does
he really address him directly.

614
00:57:41,760 --> 00:57:45,280
The nearest he comes to that
is to ask the question, why?

615
00:57:45,280 --> 00:57:49,240
And even then,
he seems uncertain as to whether
God is actually listening.

616
00:57:49,240 --> 00:57:55,880
His music provides us, his fellow
human beings, with comfort,
glimpses of a transient beauty,

617
00:57:55,880 --> 00:58:03,280
and perhaps the promise after
death of a long sought-for
and well-deserved rest.

618
00:58:12,840 --> 00:58:17,800
In the next episode of Sacred Music,
my journey takes me to Paris

619
00:58:17,800 --> 00:58:23,880
to discover the exquisitely French
church music of Gabriel Faure
and Francis Poulenc.

